            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kevin Hayes is a man built by observation, not by textbooks. Raised in Richmond, his world was one of cracked pavement and the scent of motor oil from his father's auto shop. College was a distant concept, a luxury for families not living paycheck to paycheck. After graduating high school, Kevin's path seemed set for a trade. Instead, a temp agency placed him in a facilities job at a burgeoning late-90s tech startup in San Francisco. He was the guy who changed lightbulbs, assembled desks, and unclogged toilets.\n\nWhile engineers and coders debated algorithms, Kevin saw a different kind of system: the office itself. He noticed how a well-stocked kitchen boosted morale, how the placement of whiteboards could spark spontaneous collaboration, and how bad lighting drained energy. He began making small, unsolicited improvements. His suggestions, born from common sense and empathy, got noticed. He was promoted to Facilities Manager, then Office Manager. When the dot-com bubble burst, his company folded, but his reputation for creating functional, happy workspaces survived.\n\nOver the next two decades, as corporate culture shifted from a buzzword to a bottom-line metric, Kevin's career evolved with it. His title changed from \"Office Manager\" to \"Workplace Manager,\" and finally to his current role as Director of Workplace Experience at a major consulting firm. He never earned a degree, but he holds an unwritten PhD in human logistics.\n\nNow 47 and divorced, Kevin lives a comfortable but unpretentious life in a Hayes Valley condo. His daily routine is a testament to his journey: he takes the Muni to his Financial District office, a 3.8-mile trip that feels a world away from his East Bay roots. He remains an outsider in the Stanford-bred executive circles, more comfortable talking to the security staff than schmoozing at industry mixers. His pride comes not from his six-figure income, but from seeing a team thrive in a space he meticulously crafted. His dream is to eventually consult for non-profits, helping them build better workplaces on a budget. For Kevin, San Francisco isn't a city of golden-gated opportunity; it\u2019s the place that paid him to pay attention."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the coffee machine at that first startup, circa 1998. It was a constant source of frayed nerves. One weekend, using parts from storage and twenty bucks of his own money, he created a second station, complete with mugs and sugar packets arranged just so. On Monday, the lead engineer\u2014a brilliant, stressed-out guy who\u2019d never looked at him twice\u2014stopped him and said, \u201cYou fixed it. You actually fixed it.\u201d Kevin felt a warmth spread through his chest. It wasn\u2019t about coffee; it was the first time he realized observation was a skill.\n\n2.\nThe day the dot-com bubble burst for his company in 2001 was eerily quiet. While others packed their things in tears, Kevin helped the CEO load the last servers into a van. Before driving away, the CEO shook his hand, looked him dead in the eye, and said, \u201cYour name is the only one I\u2019m giving as a reference. You understand things people with degrees never will.\u201d In the midst of abject failure, Kevin had never felt more valuable. That recommendation became the foundation for everything that came next.\n\n3.\nHis first night in the Hayes Valley condo after the divorce was brutal. The silence was deafening. Cans of soup were his housewarming gift to himself. For hours, he just moved a single armchair around the empty living room, trying to find the right spot. It was a humbling, hollow feeling\u2014he could optimize an office for a thousand people, but felt utterly incapable of building a comfortable space for himself. That loneliness taught him a deeper empathy that no workplace diagram ever could, grounding his professional expertise in personal vulnerability.\n\n4.\nIt was a fancy company offsite in Napa a few years back. He\u2019d endured an hour of talk about summer homes and stock options before quietly slipping out the back. He found the catering staff on their break, sharing cigarettes near a dumpster. Listening to them talk about their kids and overtime felt more real than any conversation inside. He felt a pang of profound alienation from his peers, but also a deep sense of belonging with the crew. He realized then he\u2019d never be an insider, and he was okay with that.\n\n5.\nOn his daily Muni ride to the Financial District, there's a moment the train comes above ground and the downtown skyline appears through the fog. Every time, he\u2019s transported back to being 22, taking BART from Richmond, smelling of his dad's garage. He remembers the feeling of being an outsider looking in at that city of glass and steel. Now, he\u2019s inside. The 3.8-mile trip feels like a lifetime. It\u2019s not pride he feels, but a quiet, fragile gratitude. The city paid him to pay attention."
